{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_kendall_ver01/data/sn82014085/00393346826/1945092401/0280.xml":{"full_text":"Tall Tower\nTopics\nBY THX MAM CN TO TO WTO\nGood Evening.\n_\u2022\nASTERS IN A VASE\n(BuggMted by a Reproduction of a Painting by this Title Appear*\nInf in a Recent Issue of The Christian Science Monitor)\nYou can have your red red roses,\nChrysanthemums are swell In their place,\nOladloll are magnificent,\nBut say\u2014asters In a vase\nMake a lovely picture,\nUp to the minute, also quaint,\nA picture you can bet\nAn artist loves to paint.\nAsters that are life-sized\nThe charming bouquet a part\nOf a truly decorative scheme,\nStill life they call It In art.\nYou can have your varl-colored pompons,\nCarnations are swell In their place,\nBut Is there a finer eyeful\nThan asters In a vase!\nHere\u2019s a question. Was the late John McCormack\njust a good singer of Irish songs and popular sentimental\nbut pleasing ballads, or was he a great artist who could\nmake such songs works of art, but who was primarily a\ngreat musician and artist whose presentation of the\nclassics and operatic arias was such that he was consid\nered one of the finest lyric tenors of his day? Waterbur\nians who heard him several times In Waterbury and jour\nneyed to New Haven, Hartford and New York to hear him\nat least once a year will perhaps agree with us and a\nwriter to the New York Herald Tribune that \u201cMcCormack\nwas superb In taste, execution and enunciation when he\nsang the old bel canto airs,\u201d and also that \"he was mig\nniflcent in the songs of Hugo Wolf and in folk songs.\u201d\nTbe writer that we mention, a New York man, was In dis\nagreement concerning an editorial, laudatory In some re\nspects, that appeared in the New York Heraid Tribune\nwhich evaluated the musicianship in a somewhat indif\nferent fashion; that is to say, ranking him only as a fine\nsinger of Irish and popular ballads; that this was his\ngreat appeal. True this excellent singing of such songs\nwas part of his general appeal, and he sang these with\nthe same fine phrasing and depth of musical feeling as\nhe did \u201cH mio tesoro\u201d from \u201cDon Giovanni\u201d which the\nwriter to the Herald mentions. He continues \u201cBut\nwho could touch him in Mozart and Handel? Bernard\nShaw, once a captious music critic, said that McCor\nmack\u2019s recording of \"II mio tesoro\u201d from \u201cDon Giovan\nni\u201d was the phonograph record he himself would have\nchosen to make if he\u2019d wanted to be immortalized by a\nrecord.\u201d Let\u2019s be fair, friends, to John McCormack, great\nIrish lyric tenor, who gave us \u201cMother Machree\u201d and\n\u201cSleeping Christ-Child\" with equal perfection as to pur\nity of tone and musicianship.\nWhat next? Folks will soon be carrying radios in\ntheir handbags according to postwar news. Here\u2019s an\nother trick. Tomorrow\u2019s raincoat will also fit in the\nfeminine pocketbook, This has become an age of rain\ncoats, absolute musts In a lady\u2019s, or a gentleman\u2019s\nwardrobe. Just note the colorful ones worn on our city\nstreets, as you walk the ways or board the busses. The\nnew raincoat Is so inconspicuous, apparently, when not\nworn, that you start out on a sunshiny day garbed for\na pleasant day. Later in the day you wend your way\nhome tain coated. How come? Your raincoat reposed\namong the knickknacks and scarcities such as ciga\nrettes, matches, tissues, lipstick, rationbook, many-sec\ntloned billfold, and suchlike. Its use was perfected for\nthe Army, but there\u2019s no reason why any of us can\u2019t in\nclude a raincoat of this sort in the handy pocketbook\nof goodly dimensions.\nWitnesses Jap Surrender On the U. S. S.\nTrippe in Apaan Bay, Pagan Island, Sept. 2\u2014(Delayed)\n\u2014Charles Duffany, 22, S 1/c, USNR, 95 Tracey street,\nThomaston, Conn., today witnessed the surrender of the\nJapanese garrison on this island from this destroyer.\nCommodore Vernon F. Grant, USN, accepted the surren\nder from MaJ. Gen. Umachachl Amau, island com\nmander, on his flagship nearby. The Trippe carried\nthe surrender proposal here recently from Saipan. The\nship is a veteran of action in the Atlantic and the Med\niterranean and was part of the escort for the vessel which\ncarried President Roosevelt to the Cairo conference in\n1943.\nNewsy Highlights Tonight is the night when\nfriends of \u201cDan\u201d Mahaney gather at Waverly Inn to\ncelebrate his appointment as county commissioner.\nBest of luck, Dan, we know of no one who Is more de\nserving of a \u201cbreak\u201d and whose loyalty should be rec\nognised Police Sergeant James Magner will be the\nprincipal speaker tomorrow noon at the weekly lunch\neon of the Rotary Club. Mr. and Mrs. George Kar-'\nnofsky have returned from New York City where they\ncelebrated their 15th wedding anniversary. George was\ngiven a citation and elected district sehior commander\nand Mrs. Karnofsky was elected district president at\nthe recent legion state convention. Many, many happy\nyears George and Sophie! Ray Walker, chairman\nof Corp. Coyle Post Drum Corps, has issued 100 Invita\ntions to various drum corps in the state. Most of them\nwill be here Next Saturday afternoon and evening.\nThere should be plenty of music when the colorful\nparade Is staged And the week after the legion\nsponsors Its annual clambake at Guertin\u2019s Grove\nThese young World War 2 veterans are sure pepping\nup the veterans\u2019 organizations They will be plenty\nof activities from now on. These \u201ctransfusions\u201d do\nwork Bon Voyage to Augustus Sabin Chase, who\nloft today to resume his duties in the consular service\nIn China. Having been a prisoner of the \u201cJaps\u201d back in\n1942 and having served more than 20 yegrs in the\nOrient, he knows his Chinese and Japanese. Maybe he\nwill be meeting some of the many Waterbury boys now\n\"sweating It out\u201d in the Far East. Meeting an American\nofficial from home would be a thrill. At least it would\nbo a welcome change from getting Icy stares from\nBrass Hats.\nFASHIONS ARE FUN\nHat* vary from cock-eyed peanut*\nTo immenae one* reaembling boulder*,\nAnd fickle faahlon ha* decreed\nHigh neckline* and wide choulder*.\n\u25a0h\nGood Night.\nSchwellenbach\u2019s New Powers Face Tough\nTest In Solving Detroit's Labor Turmoil\nS. Barton Heath, NEA Staff Correspondent, is making a surrey\nof reconversion problems In the nation\u2019s leading Industrial cities.\nHere Is his report on troubled Detroit.\nBY S. BURTON HEATH\nNEA Staff Correspondent\nDetroit, Sept. 24\u2014Whether by choice or because* his hand Is forced,\nSecy. Lewis Schwellenbach Is testing the Labor Department\u2019s new powers\nIn the toughest laboratory he could have found.\nIf, by virtue of the broadened authority vested In him by President\nTruman, Schwellenbach Is able to get the automobile Industry Into pro\nduction without a major labor war, he ought not to worry about any\ntiling else ne may einmuuwi\nBut If he fails, then in one way\nor another the explosion here is go\ning to spread in all directions\u2014a\nsplitting economic a'or.i starting a\nseries of explosions that may well\ncause Incalculable damage.\nThe United Automobile Workers\n(CIO) is demanding that the three\nbig automobile manufacturers pay\nslightly more, for a basic 40-hour\nweek without overtime, than*they\npaid at the height of the war boom\nfor an overtime week.\nThe UAW computes the straight\ntime average hourly pay for the in\ndustry as 11.17 an hour, which is\n$46.80 for a 40-hour week. Add the\nSecretary of Labor Lewi* Bchwell\nenbach, granted new power* by\nPresident Truman, faoe* major\nteit In effort to set automotive\nproduction *tarted again.\n30 per cent raise that Is demanded\nand a basic week's pay would aver\nage $60.64. This Is $1.34 more than\nthe UAW says the average auto\nworker took home at the peak of the\nwar boom, Including overtime and\nmaking no allowance for Income tax\nand War Bond deductions.\nThe automobile workers consti\ntute only one of many Industry\ngroups, generally represented by\nCIO unions, that arc demanding a\nwage raise sufficient so that, for a\nshorter work week, their \u201ctake\nhome\" pay will be as great as dur\ning the war. More often than not,\nthe same 30 per cent figure Is used.\nThe Akron rubber workers have\nannounced that they want such a\nraise., Bo have the Pittsburgh steel\nworkers and the CIO oil refinery\nworkers and many others.\nIndustry conditions differ. It Is\nby no means probable that other\nworkers would get exactly the same\narrangement that the UAW even\ntually exacts from the automobile\nUnited Press\nAgain Leads\nWith News\nShanghai, Sept. 34.\u2014(UP)\u2014The\nUnited Press today became the first\nAmerican news agency to make a\ncompleto news file available to\nliberated Shanghai's two dally news\npapers\u2014the Evening Post and Mer\ncury and the Morning Herald.\nTho Post and Mercury published\nIts first edition since Pearl Harbor.\nThe Herald Is published by Soh\nChaun Pao, who during the war pub\nlished the National Herald at\nChungking. The Herald has taken\nover the Shanghai Times plant,\nclosed by the Chinese government\nfro the newspaper\u2019s collaborationist\nactivities.\nUnited Press dispatches In the\nChinese languages are distributed\nthroughout China by the Central\nNews Agency of China. The United\nPress was the only American service\nmaintaining an unbroken Incoming\nand outgoing service In Pree China\nthroughout the war with bureaus In\nChungking and Kunming.\nThe Argentine Government Is\nbuying thta country's entire crop of\nlinseed, corn and wheat at fixed\nprices this year. _\ntram loss of\nCJtrl* r Women I If you loas ao much dur\ning monthly period* that you faal weak,\n\u201cdragged out\"\u2014thta may be due to low\nblood Hon. So try Lydia x. Plnkham'a\nTim are on* of tne beat hom* way* to\nhalp build up rad blood In auch caaea.\nPlnkham'a Tablata are on* of th* great\naat blood-iron tonic* you can buy.\nFollow label direction*.\nIfia L Nattia\u2019t TMAIW\nWe Can Recap\nYour Tire*\n8 HOUR SERVICE\nNo appointment* needed.\nOur factory method* and\nproduction of over 100 tire*\nper day make* this quick\neervice poaalble.\nWaterbary'* Pioneer Kecapper*.\nITMITCP\nEQUaSQQEBBBB!\n36 Jsffsrson St.\nTel. 1-1141\nmakers, whether that proves to be\nall or nothing or a compromise.\nBut the UAW, powerful, skilled\nIn strike techniques, with a big war\nchest, undoubtedly will prove to be\nthe bell-wether In tha. fight of\nworkers to kepp their weekly pay\nfrom decreasing now that the war\nIs over and overtime has become\nrare, Instead of being routine.\nThe automobile workers have an\nnounced a strategy that adds new\nwrinkles to traditional methods.\nThey say that they are going to\ntake the Big Three one at a time.\nFirst, unless General Motors gives\nthe 30 per cent raise, the UAW\nsays It will call out OM'i 350,000\nemployees, proclaim a boycott on\nOM products, permit Chrysler and\nFord to continue production, and\nlet General Motors watch Its rivals\nskim the cream off the big, eager\nautomobile market created by al\nmost four productionless years.\n\u201cDIVIDE AND CONQUER\u201d\nThen presumably assuming the\nGeneral Motors will capitulate to\nprotect Its consumer good will\u2014a\nsecond company will be struck In\nthe same manner. Apparently\nClyysler has been chosen to lie\nIdle while General Motors and Ford\nsell automobiles and make friends.\nWhen Ford\u2019s turn comes the union\nwould not expect him to hold out\nlong.\nBecause of the overwhelming\nascendancy of the Big Three In\nthe automotive field, and their\nbitter competition for sales, the\nUAW is working In the one In\ndustry In which Its announced\nstrategy would appear to have\ngreatest possibility of success.\nIf one or more of the big com\npanies Is shut down very long,\nthe economic ripples thus started\nwould spread far and wide, cur\nr\nIn an effort to rattle Kelsey-Hayes Wheel Co. itrlke which hat tied\nup the Ford anembly line, Richard T. Frankenateen, center, CAW\n(CIO) vice-president and Detroit mayoralty candidate, has met with\nmanagement and Local 174 representatives. Here he discusses Issues\nwith Joseph Plasa, left, chairman of the striking local, and Chester\nMullins, committeeman.\ntailing or sometime* destroying\nemployment by suppliers and\nraw material producers. The steel\nIndustry would be hit hard. The\nspeedy reconversion that Is neces\nsary to prevent a postwar slump\nfrom becoming a postwar depression,\nmight prove Impossible.\nIf the UAW wins all or much\nof Its demanded Increase, that\nwould be a signal for every\nstrongly organised Industry, where\novertime ha* given way to normal\nwork weeks, to go all out for a\nsimilar raise.\nThe companies, thus far, have\nsaid little about the union's de\nmands. If history repeats, they\nwill say, as many others do say,\nthat such a raise would necessi\ntate price Increases that would\nset oft the wildest Inflation. The\nunion denies this, In advance.\nSAY PROFITS FANTASTIC\nA spokesman for the UAW told\nme that the union contends the\n30 per cent Increase could be ab\nsorbed by the major companies\nwithout change In 1942 prices and\nwithout menace to legitimate pro\nfits.\n\"Certain of the companies make\nfantastically large profits.\u201d he said.\n\"In many years those profits arc\nequal to the companies' payroll. A\n30 per cent addition to the payroll\nwould still leave very lafge profits.\n\"Also, the automobile Industry\nnow Is entering a market where,\nfor some time to come, there will be\nno selling problem. The manufac\nturer has only to make the car, and\nlet some eager buyer get a chance\nat It. In the past, cars have been\nsold under highly competitive con\nditions, so that selling costs have\nbecome as great as, and perhaps\ngreater than manufacturing costs.\n\"This Is a mass production Indus\ntry, so set up that It can make\nenormous profits Just as long as It\noan operate at capacity. Well, for\ntwo or three years It will be able to\noperate at capacity and dispose of\nIts product without selling effort or\nexpense.\"\nSecretary Schwellenbach has sent\n19 conciliators here to try to find\nsome way of reconciling these union\nclaims with the companies' as yet\nunclarlfled counter contentions\u2014\nsome way of reconciling the natural\nhuman aversion to a \u201ctake home\u201d\npay cut with the fact that there Is\na manpower surplus In sight\u2014some\nway of keeping the entire national\nreconversion from being disastrous\nly delayed by a prolonged shut\ndown In the key automobile Indus\ntry.\nNew Machine I\nRemovesSteel\nIn War Debris\nBrussels, Sept. 94\u2014(UP)-Belgian\nengineers have designed a new ma\nchine to \"de-steel\" steel reinforced\nconcrete and hasten the Job of\nclearing Europe\u2019s debris.\nThey have estimated that their\nnew machine will shorten by as\nmuch as six months the Job of\npreparing bombed factonr sites for\nreconstruction. Seldom does bomb\ning leave modem factories in the\n\u201crubble-to-dust\u201d state popularised\nby wartime descriptions. The Gen\neral Motors plant at'Antwerp Is an\nexample. It was totally destroyed,\nbut left heaped on Its site were\nblocks of concrete, some weighing\nhundreds of tons.\nTo demolish these steel-reln\nforced Mocks by pneumatic drills\nand picks would be an overwhelm\ning Job. Dynamiting was out of the\nquestion because of nearby Instal\nlations In comparatively undamaged\nstates. First estimates were that at\nleast one full year would be needed\nto clear the site.\nBut the Belgian engineers, em\nployed by the engineering firm,\n\"Entreparses Blaton Aubert,\" adop\nted an old French technique, made\nsome Improvements, and came up\nwith the \"steel extractor.\" This\ndevice pulls out the steel reinforcing\nbars and leaves the concrete block\neasy met for pneumatic drills.\nThe \"steel extractor\" grips one\nend of the long steel bars and, ex\nerting nine tons pressure, yanks\nthe steel loose from the concrete.\nThe machine actually grips so\ntightly It contracts the steel bar\u2019s\ndiameter by a fraction of an Inch.\nIt weighs only 400 pounds and can\nbe handled by as few as two men.\nSKYSCRAPER CAMERA\nPawtucket, R. I. CUP) Narra\ngansett Park race track has the\nhighest camera tower In the United\nStates. Photo finishes are snapped\nfrom the lofty perch of 08 feet,\nwhich Insures an unusually sharp\nangle. The second highest tower, 73\nfeet, Is at Belmont Park,\nBULLET MARKS OF 1776\noBston (UP)\u2014Some of th* tomb\nstones In the ancient Copp's Hill\nBurying Oround still bear bullet\nmarks Inflicted by British troops in\ntarget practice during the siege\nof oBston In 1776.\nSeeks Naval Power 1\n(International)\nAppearing before tbe Rowe Naval\nAffaire Committee, considering\nthe question of naval poaeetlme\nstrength, Secretary of the Navy\nJamee Forrfetal urged a powerful\nfleet, with an aecent on plane car\nriers that could carry atom bombs\nwhen needed.\nEpes Awaits\nVerdict\nOn Appeal\nColumbia, S. C\u201e Sept. at. (UP)\u2014\nThe life sentence given Samuel C.\nEpes, Saturday had no effect on\nhu appetite today as he waited for\nOeneral Sessions Judge A. L, Gas\nton to rule on his motion for a\nnew trial.\nEpes ate heartily and slept well\nin his county Jail cell.\nJudgo Gaston will rule this week.\nIf the motion Is denied, Epes will\nappeal to the state supremo .court.\nEpes ,a former army lieutenant,\nwas convicted of giving hie wife\nan overdose of sodium seconal tab\nlets and burying her In a foxhole\nwhile she still was alive.\nI\nA frank statement\nabout\nt\nthe gasoline situation\nHEN the history of World War H is\nwritten, the contributions of the Ameri\ncan oil industry will make a big chapter.\nSince Pearl Harbor, for instance, it refined\n90 billion gallons of gas\u201482% of all the gas\nproduced by the United Nations. This year,\nU. S. production of that super fuel, aviation\ngas, reached the incredible total of 22 million\ngallons per day! We, the American Oil\nCompany and the Pan American Refining\nCorporation, are proud of our part in this\ngreat achievement.\nNow the oil industry is rapidly being con\nverted to peacetime use. Tankers are being\nreleased. Restrictions of all sorts are being\nlifted. Of course, all this can\u2019t be done in a\nday. Benefits for motorists are coming. First\ncame the end of rationing. Better grade\ngasoline is rapidly going back to the pumps.\nPetroleum science bas learned a tot in war.\nGreat progress has been made. There wiN\nbe better gasolines\u2014yes I But they won\u2019t be\natomic. No fuels wifi take you zooming to'\nMars. They won\u2019t make your oar into a B-29.\nI\nOur fuels wtH embody alt of the latest\nscientific advances of die oil industry.\nBehind them are the great facilities of the\nAmerican Oil Company and its affiliate,\nPan American Refining Corporation.\nWe don\u2019t want to engage in a battle of\nadjectives about them. We just want to\nremind you of the pre-war reputation of\nAmoco-Gas and American Gas\u2014and promise\nyou that every advancement petroleum\nscience has made wiH be embodied in these\ntwo fine motor fuels in fuM measure.\nAMOCO-GAS and AMERICAN GAS have always been honest products\n\u2014honestly described. You will buy with confidence knowing: that no finer\n\nmotor fuels can be made. It\u2019s not what\u2019s in the ads\u2014it\u2019s what\u2019s in the pumps.\nTHE AMERICAN POLICY\nOur policy was\u2014and still is\u2014to offer honest vatuet,\nhonestly describedto market distinctive and better\nproducts, to work constantly towards their improvement,\nto sell them at fair prices, and to render efficient service.\nm\nf\nAMERICAN OIL COMPANY","height":"28008","width":"20468"}}
